rom their social contexts or regarding them as merely illustrative of theological ideas, Morgan situates both Protestant and Catholic art within the domain of devotional practice, ritual, personal narrative, and the sacred space of the home. In addition, he examines how popular icons have been rooted in social concerns ranging from control of human passions to notions of gender, creedal orthodoxy, and friendship. Also discussed is the coupling of images with texts in the attempt to control meanings and to establish markers for one's community and belief. Drawing from the fields of music, sociology, theology, philosophy, psychology, and aesthetics,Visual Piety is the first book to bring to specialist and lay reader alike an understanding of religious imagery's place in the social formation and maintenance of everyday American life.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian art and symbolismxModern period, 1500-. 0aChristian art and symbolismxUnited States. 0aChristian art and symbolismyModern period, 1500-. 0aChristian art and symbolismzUnited States. 0aChristian art and symbolism. 0aPopular culturexUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aPopular culture. 0aSpiritualityxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aSpiritualityxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aSpiritualityxHistory. 0aSpiritualityzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSpiritualityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSpiritualityzUnited StatesxHistoryyModern period, 1500-. 4aChristianity. 4aGeneral. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh1 aMorgan, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052